 These include in-depth analyses of his celebrated and lesser known novels, short stories, theme park designs, screen and comic book adaptations, film direction and production, sketches and book illustrations, as well as responses to his material from critics and fan communities. Clive Barker: Dark imaginer reveals the breadth and depth of Barker’s distinctive dark vision, which continues to fascinate and flourish.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre), EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror tales, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aGothic 2018. 4aGothic 2019. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh  a1980s British politics.  aAdaptation.  aBodies.  aBooks of Blood.  aBritish cultural anxieties.  aBritish horror fiction.  aClive Barker.  aComic Books.  aFantasy.  aFilm Studies.  aGothic fiction.  aGothic.  aHellraiser.  aHorror.  aLord of Illusions.  aMister B. Gone.  aNightbreed.  aTortured Souls.  aWeaveworld.  aauteur.  afilm direction.  afilm production.  aliterary Criticism.  amelodrama.  aneoliberal British conservatism.  apolitical radicalism.  aqueer culture.1 aAdams, Mark Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherry, Brigid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorstorphine, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDownes, Daragh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Gareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Darryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNí Fhlainn, Sorcha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNí Fhlainn, Sorcha, ee